member.name: T:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Data.Host
member.summary: Represents the fundamentals for a host system and environment.
member.remarks: The purpose of this host architecture is primarily to make unit testing of the VS Data components possible by isolating external calls so they can be replaced at unit test time by mock implementations. This has the added benefit of making it easy to identify exactly what external calls are being made by a component. This architecture is also used as a place to isolate all icky interop related code, especially VS interop. This is very much a partial class and requires completion as either a standalone host (StandaloneHost.cs) or a package host (PackageHost.cs).
member.summary: Represents a standalone host system and environment.
member.remarks: This addition to the fundamental host class enables a host that can be used in a standalone manner, that is, it does not rely on a package to initialize and close it. The System service is in a valid state for the lifetime of the process and the Environment service is valid for the lifetime of a particular instance of the host that is constructed with a global service provider. This code is included directly in assemblies that are unable to rely on the package host because the code may run when that host is not initialized or the assembly is not in a position where it can reference the host assembly, e.g. it is in the GAC.

member.name: M:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Data.Host.GetServiceObject``1(System.IServiceProvider,``0@)
member.summary: Gets a top-level service object into the specified storage.
member.remarks: This method first tries to get the service object from the specified service provider, then falls back to instantiating the default service. At unit test time, the service provider may offer a mock of the service object and so this will be used. At run time, the default service will always be instantiated and stored so the next time it is requested we return the same object. This stored value is also used to determine whether the service should be disposed as we should not dispose one that was supplied by the service provider.

member.name: M:Microsoft.VisualStudio.Data.HostServices.Environment.CreateManagedInstance(System.Guid)
member.remarks: We implement this method from scratch instead of calling into ILocalRegistry.CreateInstance() because doing that requires marshaling to the UI thread when not called from the UI thread. If the background thread is currently holding a lock on an object that the UI thread could potentially be waiting on, the process would become deadlocked. Since there are a number of cases where this can occur, we must implement this method ourselves.
